1. What is a firewall?
A firewall is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on a defined set of security rules. It acts as a barrier between a trusted internal network and untrusted external networks (like the internet).

2. Difference between stateful and stateless firewall?
Feature	Stateless Firewall (Packet Filtering)	Stateful Firewall (Stateful Inspection)
Inspection	Examines each packet in isolation.	Tracks the state of active connections.
Context	No knowledge of previous packets or connections.	Maintains a state table of active sessions.
Security	Less secure; easily fooled by crafted packets.	More secure; ensures incoming packets are part of an established, legitimate session.
Example	An incoming response to a request you sent out would still need an explicit rule to be allowed through.	An incoming response is automatically allowed if the firewall sees a matching, existing outgoing request in its state table.

